\begin_layout Standard

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 a random variable from the Pareto distribution, characterized by a scale parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $k>0$
\end_inset

 and a shape parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>1$
\end_inset

, with cdf 
\begin_inset Formula $F_X(x)=1-(\frac{k}{x})^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

. 
\begin_inset Formula \[\text{The expecation of $X$ is then defined and equal  }E(X)=\dfrac{k\alpha}{\alpha-1}\]
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[\text{Furthermore } L(F_X)=\dfrac{E(X)}{E(X)-k}=\dfrac{k\alpha}{\alpha-1} \left( \dfrac{k\alpha}{\alpha-1}-k \right)^{-1}=\dfrac{k\alpha}{\alpha-1} \left( \dfrac{k}{\alpha-1} \right)^{-1}=\dfrac{k\alpha}{\alpha-1}  \dfrac{\alpha-1}{k}=\alpha\]
\end_inset

It follows the plug-in estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\alpha}=L(F_n)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $F_n$
\end_inset

 is the empirical distribution function of the sample 
\begin_inset Formula $\pmb{X}=(X_1,\ldots,X_n)$
\end_inset

. 
\begin_inset Formula \[L(F_n)=\dfrac{\sum_{i=1}^n X_i}{\sum_{i=1}^n X_i-k}\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph

b)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

In a similar fashion, 
\begin_inset Formula $T(F_X)=\dfrac{Var(X)}{k^2}=\dfrac{\alpha}{(\alpha-1)^2(\alpha-2)}=\theta$
\end_inset

. Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\theta}=T(F_n)=\dfrac{1}{nk^2}\sum_{i=1}^n(X_i-\overline{X})^2$
\end_inset

 is the plug-in estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

